 "segments": [
  {
   "start": 0.0,
   "end": 4.7,
   "text": "Pinyin, the system that spells Chinese with the Latin alphabet, was originally built to"
  },
  {
   "start": 4.7,
   "end": 7.34,
   "text": "do one thing, replace Chinese characters completely."
  },
  {
   "start": 7.92,
   "end": 10.88,
   "text": "The plan was to let the alphabet quietly kill them off."
  },
  {
   "start": 11.16,
   "end": 13.58,
   "text": "It failed, and today it does the exact opposite."
  },
  {
   "start": 14.14,
   "end": 18.12,
   "text": "Pinyin is the system that writes Chinese sounds using our familiar ABC letters."
  },
  {
   "start": 18.54,
   "end": 23.42,
   "text": "It was created in the 1950s by a committee led by a man named Zhou Yuguang, who's often"
  },
  {
   "start": 23.42,
   "end": 24.72,
   "text": "called the father of Pinyin."
  },
  {
   "start": 25.04,
   "end": 29.28,
   "text": "But for many of the reformers behind it, including Mao himself, Pinyin wasn't meant"
  },
  {
   "start": 29.28,
   "end": 33.16,
   "text": "to just sit politely beside the characters, it was meant to gradually replace them."
  },
  {
   "start": 33.56,
   "end": 37.02,
   "text": "The thinking went, the characters were too hard, holding back literacy."
  },
  {
   "start": 37.52,
   "end": 40.34,
   "text": "The future was a simple alphabet, like most of the world used."
  },
  {
   "start": 40.86,
   "end": 43.38,
   "text": "Pinyin was the bridge to get there, now the honest part."
  },
  {
   "start": 43.78,
   "end": 47.62,
   "text": "That goal was never fully written into law, and it was never officially declared dead,"
  },
  {
   "start": 47.78,
   "end": 48.02,
   "text": "either."
  },
  {
   "start": 48.18,
   "end": 49.96,
   "text": "It was simply buried."
  },
  {
   "start": 50.32,
   "end": 54.74,
   "text": "As literacy rose and the country modernized, the appetite to throw out thousands of years"
  },
  {
   "start": 54.74,
   "end": 58.5,
   "text": "of characters faded, and Pinyin got quietly reclassified as a helper."
  },
  {
   "start": 58.5,
   "end": 61.16,
   "text": "A way to teach pronunciation and sound out characters."
  },
  {
   "start": 61.66,
   "end": 65.78,
   "text": "Not to replace them, and here's the twist, Pinyin didn't kill the characters, it saved"
  },
  {
   "start": 65.78,
   "end": 66.04,
   "text": "them."
  },
  {
   "start": 66.36,
   "end": 69.34,
   "text": "Because today, how do you type Chinese on a phone or a keyboard?"
  },
  {
   "start": 69.74,
   "end": 72.32,
   "text": "You type the Pinyin, and pick the character from a list."
  },
  {
   "start": 72.74,
   "end": 76.4,
   "text": "The system built to replace the characters is now the main reason they thrive in the"
  },
  {
   "start": 76.4,
   "end": 77.02,
   "text": "digital age."
  },
  {
   "start": 77.48,
   "end": 81.06,
   "text": "So Pinyin was a weapon aimed straight at Chinese characters, that completely missed"
  },
  {
   "start": 81.06,
   "end": 83.06,
   "text": "and became their life support instead."
  },
  {
   "start": 83.52,
   "end": 86.76,
   "text": "The bridge meant to lead away from the characters is now the bridge everyone uses"
  },
  {
   "start": 86.76,
   "end": 87.42,
   "text": "to reach them."
  },
  {
   "start": 87.42,
   "end": 89.54,
   "text": "Want to actually start learning Chinese?"
  },
  {
   "start": 90.44,
   "end": 94.2,
   "text": "Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io"
  }
 ]
}